00:12:28.960 --> 00:12:33.635
So you can successfully
reproduce this pattern,

00:12:33.635 --> 00:12:38.720
but what does it tell you about
what's going on?

00:12:38.720 --> 00:12:40.048
What good is that pattern?
 

00:12:40.048 --> 00:12:43.250
The pattern tells you that if
you repeat the experiment with

00:12:43.250 --> 00:12:46.452
this electron gun a million
times or a billion times and you

00:12:46.452 --> 00:12:51.889
plotted the histogram patiently,
the histogram will eventually

00:12:51.889 --> 00:12:55.440
fill out and take this shape.
 

00:12:55.440 --> 00:12:59.331
So this wave is not the wave
associated with a huge stream of

00:12:59.331 --> 00:13:00.110
electrons.
 

00:13:00.110 --> 00:13:03.629
A single electron in the lab is
controlled by this wave.

00:13:03.629 --> 00:13:06.682
You need a whole wave for 1
electron, so it's obviously not

00:13:06.682 --> 00:13:07.840
a wave of electrons.
 

00:13:07.840 --> 00:13:10.460
It's not a wave of charge,
like the wave of water.

00:13:10.460 --> 00:13:13.918
It's a mathematical function
and you are drawn to it,

00:13:13.918 --> 00:13:16.923
because the only way you know
how to get this wiggly graph is

00:13:16.923 --> 00:13:20.230
to take something with definite
wavelength and let it interfere.

00:13:20.230 --> 00:13:22.808
So you're forced to think about
this wave.

00:13:22.808 --> 00:13:26.958
And the intensity of the wave,
the brightness if you like,

00:13:26.958 --> 00:13:30.090
the square of its height,
gives you what?

00:13:30.090 --> 00:13:33.910
Gives you the graph you will
get if you repeat the experiment

00:13:33.910 --> 00:13:34.740
many times.
 

00:13:34.740 --> 00:13:36.769
And what does it mean for the
individual trial?

00:13:36.769 --> 00:13:41.220
What does it mean for the
millionth one electron?

00:13:41.220 --> 00:13:45.666
For the millionth one electron,
it gives you the odds of where

00:13:45.666 --> 00:13:48.288
it will land on that screen,
okay?

00:13:48.288 --> 00:13:50.048
You can never tell exactly
where it will be.

00:13:50.048 --> 00:13:52.610
You can tell what the odds are,
and the only way to test the

00:13:52.610 --> 00:13:55.038
statistical theory is to do the
experiment many times.

00:13:55.038 --> 00:13:57.562
And if you do it,
it works, and it seems to work

00:13:57.562 --> 00:13:59.154
for everything,
for electrons,

00:13:59.154 --> 00:14:00.360
for protons,
for photons,

00:14:00.360 --> 00:14:04.686
whatever it is,
the wavelength and momentum are

00:14:04.686 --> 00:14:07.320
connected in this fashion.
 

00:14:07.320 --> 00:14:11.333
So this wave is forced upon us,
and it gives you the odds of

00:14:11.333 --> 00:14:13.580
finding the electron somewhere.
 

00:14:13.580 --> 00:14:16.289
And we say that the
probability-- I'll be a little

00:14:16.289 --> 00:14:19.607
more precise in a minute on what
I mean by the probability to

00:14:19.607 --> 00:14:22.748
find it at a location x,
but let's just say,

00:14:22.748 --> 00:14:25.590
if you draw the graph of
Y^(2),

00:14:25.590 --> 00:14:27.668
wherever it is big,
the probability is larger;

00:14:27.668 --> 00:14:29.649
wherever it is small,
probability is small;

00:14:29.649 --> 00:14:33.480
wherever it is 0,
probability is 0.

00:14:33.480 --> 00:14:37.027
So there seems to be a function
whose amplitude or whose square

00:14:37.027 --> 00:14:38.629
gives you the probability.
 

00:14:38.629 --> 00:14:42.168
That function is called the
wave function,

00:14:42.168 --> 00:14:46.481
and we know it exists,
because it's the only way to

00:14:46.481 --> 00:14:50.279
calculate the result of this
experiment.

00:14:50.279 --> 00:14:55.327
Once you tell me that the fate
of a particle is controlled by a

00:14:55.327 --> 00:14:57.768
wave,
you're immediately led to some

00:14:57.768 --> 00:15:00.557
other conclusions,
so I'm going to tell you what

00:15:00.557 --> 00:15:01.110
they are.
 

00:15:01.110 --> 00:15:07.080
First conclusion is this:
if I make a single slit,

00:15:07.080 --> 00:15:09.720
let's call this the x
direction,

00:15:09.720 --> 00:15:12.139
let's call this the y
direction,

00:15:12.139 --> 00:15:17.591
and I'm sending a bunch of
particles in the x

00:15:17.591 --> 00:15:23.149
direction with some momentum
p_0.

00:15:23.149 --> 00:15:27.380
In Newtonian mechanics,
I can manufacture for you an

00:15:27.380 --> 00:15:31.115
electron of known momentum and
known position,

00:15:31.115 --> 00:15:34.019
or known to arbitrary accuracy.
 

00:15:34.019 --> 00:15:38.509
If Dx is the
uncertainty in my position,

00:15:38.509 --> 00:15:41.269
and Dp is the
uncertainty in momentum,

00:15:41.269 --> 00:15:44.029
I can make each of them as
small as I like.

00:15:44.029 --> 00:15:48.870
So here's an actual practical
way to prepare such a state.

00:15:48.870 --> 00:15:51.498
If I say, "Give me an
electron of known position,

00:15:51.498 --> 00:15:53.779
known momentum,"
here's what I will do.

00:15:53.779 --> 00:15:56.370
I will take a slit with a very
tiny hole in it.

00:15:56.370 --> 00:16:00.340
The width of that hole is
d, and whoever comes out

00:16:00.340 --> 00:16:03.388
on the other side,
what can I say about that

00:16:03.388 --> 00:16:04.308
particle?
 

00:16:04.308 --> 00:16:07.639
Its position has an uncertainty
of order d,

00:16:07.639 --> 00:16:11.307
because if it was not--I'm
sorry, Dy now,

00:16:11.307 --> 00:16:14.230
because this is the y
direction.

00:16:14.230 --> 00:16:15.379
Right?
 

00:16:15.379 --> 00:16:19.294
Anything who came out of hole
right after it had to have a y

00:16:19.294 --> 00:16:22.149
position, whose known to within
d.

00:16:22.149 --> 00:16:24.883
It's got to come anywhere
within the slit,

00:16:24.883 --> 00:16:25.950
but that's it.
 

00:16:25.950 --> 00:16:28.835
So that is how I have prepared
for you, that's how we filter

00:16:28.835 --> 00:16:30.450
electrons of definite position.
 

00:16:30.450 --> 00:16:32.589
And you can make
Dy as small as you

00:16:32.589 --> 00:16:34.639
like by making the slit as thin
as you like.

00:16:34.639 --> 00:16:36.288
What about its momentum?
 

00:16:36.288 --> 00:16:38.696
If you had a momentum
p_0 in the

00:16:38.696 --> 00:16:41.557
x direction,
no momentum in the y

00:16:41.557 --> 00:16:44.057
direction,
therefore py was

00:16:44.057 --> 00:16:46.308
strictly 0,
no uncertainty.

00:16:46.308 --> 00:16:49.442
Dpy is 0 and the
fellow I catch here is moving

00:16:49.442 --> 00:16:52.469
horizontally with that momentum
p_0 whose

00:16:52.469 --> 00:16:54.700
y position is within
d,

00:16:54.700 --> 00:16:56.570
and I can make the d as
small as I like.

00:16:56.570 --> 00:16:59.519
This is Newtonian physics.
 

00:16:59.519 --> 00:17:02.658
But we have now learned that
the fate of the particle is not

00:17:02.658 --> 00:17:03.669
in its own hands.
 

00:17:03.669 --> 00:17:07.000
It's contained in this wave.
 

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:11.894
So what should I do in this
context to find out what it will

00:17:11.894 --> 00:17:12.308
do?
 

00:17:12.308 --> 00:17:17.142
Any idea what I should do to
find out what will happen in

00:17:17.142 --> 00:17:20.680
this experiment,
given what we learned?

00:17:20.680 --> 00:17:21.528
Yes?
 

00:17:21.528 --> 00:17:25.338
Student: 
&gt;

00:17:25.338 --> 00:17:28.528
Prof: Right,
but how will I calculate what

00:17:28.528 --> 00:17:30.720
will happen in this experiment?
 

00:17:30.720 --> 00:17:33.680
What will decide?
 

00:17:33.680 --> 00:17:34.430
Yes?
 

00:17:34.430 --> 00:17:40.549
Student: 
&gt;

00:17:40.549 --> 00:17:42.484
Prof: Yes,
this is one hole,

00:17:42.484 --> 00:17:45.660
and a light beam is coming from
the left--

00:17:45.660 --> 00:17:47.910
I mean, a wave is coming from
the left,

00:17:47.910 --> 00:17:50.180
and if the particle has
momentum p_0,

00:17:50.180 --> 00:17:54.615
it's got some wavelength,
which is 2p

00:17:54.615 --> 00:17:57.009
ℏ/p_0.
 

00:17:57.009 --> 00:18:00.859
But if you want to know what
will happen on the other side of

00:18:00.859 --> 00:18:04.068
this slit, I have to find the
fate of that wave.

00:18:04.068 --> 00:18:07.348
Yes, you can put a screen,
but what will I see on a

00:18:07.348 --> 00:18:07.940
screen?
 

00:18:07.940 --> 00:18:12.190
Will the wave just hit this
region?

00:18:12.190 --> 00:18:14.538
You know it will spread out
from diffraction.

00:18:14.538 --> 00:18:17.670
I've told you,
the light will spread out.

00:18:17.670 --> 00:18:21.630
There are tiny wiggles we
ignore, and this point,

00:18:21.630 --> 00:18:24.410
where you get most of the
action, that angle,

00:18:24.410 --> 00:18:27.790
θ,
satisfies dsinθ=

00:18:27.790 --> 00:18:29.059
l.
 

00:18:29.059 --> 00:18:30.430
This is just wave theory.
 

00:18:30.430 --> 00:18:33.400
That's when you can pair up the
points in the slit,

00:18:33.400 --> 00:18:35.502
in the hole,
to things shifting,

00:18:35.502 --> 00:18:39.222
differing by half a wavelength,
so for every one I can find a

00:18:39.222 --> 00:18:41.920
partner that cancels it,
you will get 0 here.

00:18:41.920 --> 00:18:44.878
Beyond that,
you may get a few more rises,

00:18:44.878 --> 00:18:48.200
but it's pretty much dead
outside this cone.

00:18:48.200 --> 00:18:54.688
That means you will observe
this particle anywhere in this

00:18:54.688 --> 00:18:56.509
angular width.
 

00:18:56.509 --> 00:19:01.741
Now a particle cannot go from
this slit to there unless it had

00:19:01.741 --> 00:19:05.858
a momentum, which had a
component in the y

00:19:05.858 --> 00:19:07.058
direction.
 

00:19:07.058 --> 00:19:09.848
You cannot get there from here,
unless you have y momentum.

00:19:09.848 --> 00:19:14.910
It's the y momentum is
uncertain to within that cone.

00:19:14.910 --> 00:19:18.028
So what's the uncertainty in
the y momentum?

00:19:18.028 --> 00:19:20.663
For a vector of length
p_0 when it

00:19:20.663 --> 00:19:23.506
gets shifted by an angle
Dθ or by an angle

00:19:23.506 --> 00:19:25.384
θ,
it is just

00:19:25.384 --> 00:19:27.858
p_0xθ.
 

00:19:27.858 --> 00:19:31.343
Or, if you like,
precisely, p_0

00:19:31.343 --> 00:19:33.269
times sinθ.
 

00:19:33.269 --> 00:19:37.509
But p_0
sinθ,

00:19:37.509 --> 00:19:39.710
sinθ
is controlled by

00:19:39.710 --> 00:19:41.910
dsinθ
= l,

00:19:41.910 --> 00:19:48.720
so this is l/d.
 

00:19:48.720 --> 00:19:54.529
But l is 2p
ℏ/p_0 x d.

00:19:54.529 --> 00:19:59.324
You cancel that,
you find D py X d =

00:19:59.324 --> 00:20:02.838
2pℏ.
 

00:20:02.838 --> 00:20:07.967
That means D py D y is
roughly--forget the

00:20:07.967 --> 00:20:12.970
2p's--of our
ℏ.

00:20:12.970 --> 00:20:17.199
So you should understand this
much completely without any

00:20:17.199 --> 00:20:20.220
doubt: if the future of the
particle,

00:20:20.220 --> 00:20:22.670
the fate of the particle,
is controlled by the wave,

00:20:22.670 --> 00:20:25.382
you try to narrow the location
of the particle by making the

00:20:25.382 --> 00:20:28.759
hole smaller and smaller,
the wave fans out more and more.

00:20:28.759 --> 00:20:30.450
That's just wave theory.
 

00:20:30.450 --> 00:20:32.900
People knew this about waves
hundreds of years back.

00:20:32.900 --> 00:20:36.435
What is novel is that this wave
is going to tell you where the

00:20:36.435 --> 00:20:37.769
particle will end up.
 

00:20:37.769 --> 00:20:40.288
This wave is going to control
the odds of where the particle

00:20:40.288 --> 00:20:43.058
will end up,
and the odds are pretty much

00:20:43.058 --> 00:20:46.101
concentrated in this cone,
not of 0 opening angle,

00:20:46.101 --> 00:20:48.476
but an angle θ,
so that dsinθ

00:20:48.476 --> 00:20:49.338
= l.
 

00:20:49.338 --> 00:20:54.650
l in turn is connected to the
momentum of the particle.

00:20:54.650 --> 00:20:59.029
This is where the uncertainty
principle comes in.

00:20:59.029 --> 00:21:02.490
What Heisenberg said is,
"You had in your mind the

00:21:02.490 --> 00:21:05.887
classical notion that you can
have a particle of known

00:21:05.887 --> 00:21:07.940
position and known momentum.
 

00:21:07.940 --> 00:21:10.960
Let me see you produce that
particle.

00:21:10.960 --> 00:21:13.653
So you try to do it by putting
a slit and catching guys with a

00:21:13.653 --> 00:21:17.000
very narrow range in y,
but now you find out that the

00:21:17.000 --> 00:21:19.348
momentum gets broader and
broader,

00:21:19.348 --> 00:21:22.192
and that's the result of the
wave associated with the

00:21:22.192 --> 00:21:22.740
project.
 

00:21:22.740 --> 00:21:24.160
" It was not in the
Newtonian picture.

00:21:24.160 --> 00:21:25.358
Yes?
 

00:21:25.358 --> 00:21:28.836
Student:  Why with the
single slit, like you've drawn

00:21:28.836 --> 00:21:32.078
there, do you get the little
wiggle at the outside--?

00:21:32.078 --> 00:21:33.731
Prof: You mean,
why would it have those

00:21:33.731 --> 00:21:34.098
wiggles?
 

00:21:34.098 --> 00:21:39.230
Okay, so if I look at the
single slit, I could think of

00:21:39.230 --> 00:21:41.890
many little point sources.
 

00:21:41.890 --> 00:21:44.491
In the forward direction,
if you go very far,

00:21:44.491 --> 00:21:48.160
so you treat them as roughly
parallel, they are all in step.

00:21:48.160 --> 00:21:50.220
You've got a big maximum.
 

00:21:50.220 --> 00:21:53.942
In another direction where this
difference is l,

00:21:53.942 --> 00:21:58.300
dsinθ = l,
this guy and this guy are

00:21:58.300 --> 00:22:00.519
differing by l/2.
 

00:22:00.519 --> 00:22:03.136
Student:  So you're
assuming the slit is large

00:22:03.136 --> 00:22:05.048
enough for them to do that
________.

00:22:05.048 --> 00:22:08.844
Prof: These are little
mathematical dots inside the

00:22:08.844 --> 00:22:09.308
slit.
 

00:22:09.308 --> 00:22:13.739
You know, when you make a slit,
every point on the slit looks

00:22:13.739 --> 00:22:17.430
like a source of light,
a point source of light.

00:22:17.430 --> 00:22:19.913
They are not really light
bulbs, but if you make any hole

00:22:19.913 --> 00:22:21.864
in the wall, a light comes
through that hole,

00:22:21.864 --> 00:22:23.548
looks like it's a source of
light.

00:22:23.548 --> 00:22:26.608
I'm taking every point on the
hole to be a source of light.

00:22:26.608 --> 00:22:30.561
And what I'm saying is,
there is a direction in which

00:22:30.561 --> 00:22:33.982
it will cancel,
but if you go a little further

00:22:33.982 --> 00:22:36.720
out, it won't cancel completely.
 

00:22:36.720 --> 00:22:38.555
This is the direction for
perfect cancelation,

00:22:38.555 --> 00:22:40.391
where I can pair them,
this one with this one,

00:22:40.391 --> 00:22:41.859
that one to that one,
and so on.

00:22:41.859 --> 00:22:43.538
They pair to give 0.
 

00:22:43.538 --> 00:22:46.467
But if you move further up,
you no longer cancel

00:22:46.467 --> 00:22:48.433
completely,
but you don't add perfectly

00:22:48.433 --> 00:22:49.739
either,
so things will get better,

00:22:49.739 --> 00:22:52.420
then they'll get worse again,
and better and worse and so on.

00:22:52.420 --> 00:22:54.359
So that's the origin of that
pattern.

00:22:54.359 --> 00:22:55.779
Yes?
 

00:22:55.779 --> 00:22:57.796
Student:  So you're
saying this is the first

00:22:57.796 --> 00:22:58.200
minimum.
 

00:22:58.200 --> 00:22:59.329
After that, it would increase
_______.

00:22:59.329 --> 00:23:00.048
Prof: Yes.
 

00:23:00.048 --> 00:23:03.643
For a single slit diffraction,
the big thing in the middle is

00:23:03.643 --> 00:23:05.259
pretty much all you have.
 

00:23:05.259 --> 00:23:10.523
It's not like double slit
experiment with two holes,

00:23:10.523 --> 00:23:14.548
where you get many times the
pattern.

00:23:14.548 --> 00:23:17.460
That's because--let's
understand why that is true.

00:23:17.460 --> 00:23:22.720
Here, if these two differ by 1
wavelength, they don't differ at

00:23:22.720 --> 00:23:23.230
all.
 

00:23:23.230 --> 00:23:25.890
I can find another angle where
they differ by 2 wavelengths.

00:23:25.890 --> 00:23:27.358
They don't differ at all.
 

00:23:27.358 --> 00:23:29.642
There's only 2 sources,
so you can engineer them to

00:23:29.642 --> 00:23:32.608
differ by either 1 wavelength or
2 wavelength or 3 wavelengths.

00:23:32.608 --> 00:23:36.656
Here in a single slit,
each point is like a source of

00:23:36.656 --> 00:23:37.279
light.
 

00:23:37.279 --> 00:23:39.230
You got them all to agree.
 

00:23:39.230 --> 00:23:41.308
You can get them to agree only
in the forward direction.

00:23:41.308 --> 00:23:44.211
In any other direction,
you can get them to neutralize

00:23:44.211 --> 00:23:46.950
each other, but never for
perfect reinforcement.

00:23:46.950 --> 00:23:49.736
So you cannot get it more
than--this is the only real

00:23:49.736 --> 00:23:50.539
maximum here.
 

00:23:50.539 --> 00:23:51.769
Everything else is tiny.
 

00:23:51.769 --> 00:23:52.858
Yes?
 

00:23:52.858 --> 00:23:55.582
Student:  Why can't you
do the same trick with the

00:23:55.582 --> 00:23:58.450
double slit, where each of the
one slits has its _______?

00:23:58.450 --> 00:23:59.511
Prof: No,
in double slit,

00:23:59.511 --> 00:24:01.911
what's happening is,
we take--in double slit,

00:24:01.911 --> 00:24:05.941
the number d I used in
double slit was not the size of

00:24:05.941 --> 00:24:09.002
a slit,
but the space in between the

00:24:09.002 --> 00:24:10.000
slit, okay?
 

00:24:10.000 --> 00:24:14.163
So there I took the size of
every slit to be vanishingly

00:24:14.163 --> 00:24:14.769
small.
 

00:24:14.769 --> 00:24:18.520
That means a light coming out
of this slit spreads out

00:24:18.520 --> 00:24:21.140
completely in all directions,
okay?

00:24:21.140 --> 00:24:26.108
It's as if this packet became
that broad.

00:24:26.108 --> 00:24:32.098
Likewise a light from this one,
we are still in the first

00:24:32.098 --> 00:24:34.558
maximum of that slit.
 

00:24:34.558 --> 00:24:38.404
So you've got to understand,
in a single slit experiment of

00:24:38.404 --> 00:24:41.920
diffraction, the slit size is
what you are varying.

00:24:41.920 --> 00:24:44.518
In a double slit experiment,
the slit is taken to be

00:24:44.518 --> 00:24:47.318
mathematically point like,
so it fans out completely.

00:24:47.318 --> 00:24:50.442
It's the interference between
those two point sources that

00:24:50.442 --> 00:24:51.318
you're adding.
 

00:24:51.318 --> 00:24:54.594
They can add and cancel,
add and cancel,

00:24:54.594 --> 00:24:58.538
many, many times as you move
along this line.

00:24:58.538 --> 00:25:01.407
Okay, so what we learn is it's
when you combine waves and

00:25:01.407 --> 00:25:04.788
particles and go back and forth
that you run into the situation.

00:25:04.788 --> 00:25:08.410
So you cannot make a state of
perfect momentum.

00:25:08.410 --> 00:25:10.480
By the way, I said one thing,
I thought about it,

00:25:10.480 --> 00:25:13.808
which is incorrect,
which is, in the microscope,

