00:28:46.288 --> 00:28:47.890
But he didn't know what was
oscillating.

00:28:47.890 --> 00:28:50.340
He didn't know there's an
electric and magnetic field

00:28:50.340 --> 00:28:51.519
underneath all of that.
 

00:28:51.519 --> 00:28:54.066
But you can always read out the
wavelength without knowing

00:28:54.066 --> 00:28:54.868
what's going on.
 

00:28:54.868 --> 00:28:57.068
Likewise, we have the
wavelength.

00:28:57.068 --> 00:29:00.143
We know it comes from a
function with a well defined

00:29:00.143 --> 00:29:03.700
wavelength, so I make my first
guess to be this function.

00:29:03.700 --> 00:29:07.039
But I told you what was wrong
with this choice.

00:29:07.039 --> 00:29:10.890
You guys remember that?
 

00:29:10.890 --> 00:29:14.808
I said this function violates
the uncertainty principle.

00:29:14.808 --> 00:29:18.387
The uncertainty principle says
if you know the position to an

00:29:18.387 --> 00:29:21.285
accuracy Dx,
and if you know the momentum to

00:29:21.285 --> 00:29:25.346
accuracy Dp,
the product must be at least as

00:29:25.346 --> 00:29:29.970
big as hx some
number of order 1.

00:29:29.970 --> 00:29:34.798
We have taken the particles to
have well defined momentum.

00:29:34.798 --> 00:29:38.578
If they have well defined
momentum, Dp is 0.

00:29:38.578 --> 00:29:42.210
Dp is 0,
Dx is infinity.

00:29:42.210 --> 00:29:47.240
Now I told the square of the
wave function is the probability

00:29:47.240 --> 00:29:51.432
to find it somewhere,
and you have no idea where it

00:29:51.432 --> 00:29:52.019
is.
 

00:29:52.019 --> 00:29:56.340
In other words,
a particle of perfectly known

00:29:56.340 --> 00:30:00.269
momentum has totally unknown
position.

00:30:00.269 --> 00:30:04.517
So the probability should look
flat, Y^(2) should

00:30:04.517 --> 00:30:05.338
look flat.
 

00:30:05.338 --> 00:30:09.277
But the Y^(2),
due to cosine,

00:30:09.277 --> 00:30:11.338
of course does this.
 

00:30:11.338 --> 00:30:14.924
It prefers some locations to
another, but you're not supposed

00:30:14.924 --> 00:30:18.750
to have any preference for any
x, so we have a problem.

00:30:18.750 --> 00:30:24.300
How do I put in a wavelength
into a function whose square is

00:30:24.300 --> 00:30:24.960
flat?
 

00:30:24.960 --> 00:30:27.358
That's the problem we have.
 

00:30:27.358 --> 00:30:30.175
When you think about it,
you realize your trigonometric

00:30:30.175 --> 00:30:31.950
functions will not do the trick.
 

00:30:31.950 --> 00:30:33.930
If they have a wavelength,
their square is not flat.

00:30:33.930 --> 00:30:36.450
The square is also oscillating.
 

00:30:36.450 --> 00:30:39.865
But then what came to the
rescue is the following

00:30:39.865 --> 00:30:41.707
function,
not a cosine but

00:30:41.707 --> 00:30:44.608
Ae^(ipx)
^(/ℏ),

00:30:44.608 --> 00:30:48.910
rather than cosine
xp/ℏ.

00:30:48.910 --> 00:30:51.358
Look at this function.
 

00:30:51.358 --> 00:30:52.847
This function,
I've told you many,

00:30:52.847 --> 00:30:55.104
many times, if you don't know
your complex numbers,

00:30:55.104 --> 00:30:57.088
you're definitely going to have
trouble.

00:30:57.088 --> 00:31:02.893
It looks like a vector of
length A and angle

00:31:02.893 --> 00:31:06.838
θ,
which is px/â„ .

00:31:06.838 --> 00:31:10.410
As you vary x,
this x changes and this

00:31:10.410 --> 00:31:13.838
will rotate round,
but as it rotates the amplitude

00:31:13.838 --> 00:31:16.539
of this complex number,
absolute value of

00:31:16.539 --> 00:31:19.634
Y^(2),
which is Y times

00:31:19.634 --> 00:31:23.405
Y', which is A--
I'm taking A to be real

00:31:23.405 --> 00:31:26.346
