00:31:35.720 --> 00:31:38.075
In other words,
the complex number describing

00:31:38.075 --> 00:31:41.019
the wave function changes in
phase but not amplitude.

00:31:41.019 --> 00:31:44.608
It's the amplitude that gives
the probability.

00:31:44.608 --> 00:31:48.118
Now there is no problem with
this guy having a wavelength,

00:31:48.118 --> 00:31:50.460
because this oscillates in
x.

00:31:50.460 --> 00:31:52.974
Its real part and imaginary
part both oscillate,

00:31:52.974 --> 00:31:56.240
but the square of the real the
imaginary square is 1 [A^2].

00:31:56.240 --> 00:31:59.970
That's why the amplitude
doesn't change.

00:31:59.970 --> 00:32:04.384
So we are driven now to the
very interesting result that the

00:32:04.384 --> 00:32:08.875
wave function for a particle of
definite momentum p is

00:32:08.875 --> 00:32:09.548
this.
 

00:32:09.548 --> 00:32:12.068
So this is a very important
lesson.

00:32:12.068 --> 00:32:15.006
Let me label this function by
label p to tell you,

00:32:15.006 --> 00:32:17.313
"Hey, I'm not talking
about any old wave

00:32:17.313 --> 00:32:18.308
function."
 

00:32:18.308 --> 00:32:20.720
This guy has a definite
momentum p.

00:32:20.720 --> 00:32:28.152
Its wave function looks like
