It doesn't matter.
 

00:38:27.730 --> 00:38:30.284
You're playing around with
factors like 10 and 100 and

00:38:30.284 --> 00:38:30.670
1,000.
 

00:38:30.670 --> 00:38:33.900
I got 10^(19) here.
 

00:38:33.900 --> 00:38:36.619
So nothing you do will make any
dent on that.

00:38:36.619 --> 00:38:39.574
So in the macroscopic world,
you will not see this

00:38:39.574 --> 00:38:40.480
interference.
 

00:38:40.480 --> 00:38:45.342
Another reason you won't see it
is that the particle should have

00:38:45.342 --> 00:38:47.039
a definite momentum.
 

00:38:47.039 --> 00:38:49.338
It's got an indefinite
momentum, it's coming in with

00:38:49.338 --> 00:38:51.365
different momenta,
then each will have its own

00:38:51.365 --> 00:38:53.710
interference pattern and they'll
get washed out.

00:38:53.710 --> 00:38:57.260
Finally, I told you,
if you ever try to see which

00:38:57.260 --> 00:39:01.329
slit the particle took by
putting a light beam here,

00:39:01.329 --> 00:39:04.032
the minute you catch the
electron going through one slit

00:39:04.032 --> 00:39:07.659
or the other,
this pattern is gone.

00:39:07.659 --> 00:39:10.409
It will do this "I'm not
here and I'm not there"

00:39:10.409 --> 00:39:12.920
routine only if you never catch
it being anywhere.

00:39:12.920 --> 00:39:14.739
That's very interesting.
 

00:39:14.739 --> 00:39:17.657
The electron behaves like it
does not go through any one

00:39:17.657 --> 00:39:20.047
particular slit,
as long as you don't catch it

00:39:20.047 --> 00:39:21.480
going through one slit.
 

00:39:21.480 --> 00:39:23.768
You put enough light to catch
every electron,

00:39:23.768 --> 00:39:26.836
then you can add the numbers
and you must get the sum of the

00:39:26.836 --> 00:39:27.670
two numbers.
 

00:39:27.670 --> 00:39:30.474
Now for the atomic world,
it's possible for the electron

00:39:30.474 --> 00:39:33.280
to go for a long time without
encountering anything,

00:39:33.280 --> 00:39:36.219
and the interference effects
come into play.

00:39:36.219 --> 00:39:39.170
In a macroscopic world,
there is no way a macroscopic

00:39:39.170 --> 00:39:42.574
object can travel for any length
of time without running into

00:39:42.574 --> 00:39:43.369
something.
 

00:39:43.369 --> 00:39:44.880
It will run into other air
molecules.

00:39:44.880 --> 00:39:46.909
It will run into cosmic ray
radiation.

00:39:46.909 --> 00:39:49.936
It can collide with black body
radiation from the big bang,

00:39:49.936 --> 00:39:50.510
anything.
 

00:39:50.510 --> 00:39:53.717
The minute you have any contact
with it, this funny thing will

00:39:53.717 --> 00:39:54.349
disappear.
 

00:39:54.349 --> 00:39:56.099
So that's one reason you don't
see it.

00:39:56.099 --> 00:39:58.268
Now we can go on and on and
give other numbers.

00:39:58.268 --> 00:40:01.414
I've given examples in my
notes, which I will post later

00:40:01.414 --> 00:40:01.699
on.
 

00:40:01.699 --> 00:40:04.590
One of them is the uncertainty
principle.

00:40:04.590 --> 00:40:08.543
Why does it look like the
uncertainty principle is not

00:40:08.543 --> 00:40:09.440
important?
 

00:40:09.440 --> 00:40:13.989
Take again, this is 10^(-34).
 

00:40:13.989 --> 00:40:16.110
Everything is in MKS units.
 

00:40:16.110 --> 00:40:23.228
So take an object of mass 1
kilogram whose location is known

00:40:23.228 --> 00:40:26.849
to the accuracy of 1 proton.
 

00:40:26.849 --> 00:40:27.289
Okay?
 

00:40:27.289 --> 00:40:34.860
So this number is 10^(-15)
meters, do you understand?

00:40:34.860 --> 00:40:38.623
You take an object made of
10^(23) protons and you know its

00:40:38.623 --> 00:40:40.960
location to the width of 1
proton.

00:40:40.960 --> 00:40:43.150
That's all you don't know about
its location.

00:40:43.150 --> 00:40:44.000
That's your Dx.
 

00:40:44.000 --> 00:40:45.199
What's the Dp?
 

00:40:45.199 --> 00:40:48.592
Well, Dp is now
10 to the, what,

00:40:48.592 --> 00:40:48.969
19?
 

00:40:48.969 --> 00:40:52.199
10^(-19).
 

00:40:52.199 --> 00:40:56.010
Now Dp is
m times Dv.

00:40:56.010 --> 00:40:57.619
That's 10^(-19).
 

00:40:57.619 --> 00:41:01.659
If this is 1 kilogram,
Dv is

00:41:01.659 --> 00:41:04.420
10^(-19)meters per second.
 

00:41:04.420 --> 00:41:08.840
You don't know its velocity to
1 part in 10^(19).

00:41:08.840 --> 00:41:10.789
Now how bad is that?
 

00:41:10.789 --> 00:41:13.340
Well, suppose I start a
particle off exactly known

00:41:13.340 --> 00:41:15.630
velocity, I know where it will
be forever.

00:41:15.630 --> 00:41:19.737
But suppose I don't know the
velocity to this accuracy,

00:41:19.737 --> 00:41:22.018
and I let it run for 1 year.
 

00:41:22.018 --> 00:41:24.449
So I don't know precisely where
it is, but how bad is it?

00:41:24.449 --> 00:41:25.840
How badly do I not know?
 

00:41:25.840 --> 00:41:34.391
Well, 1 year is 10^(7) seconds,
so if it runs for 1 year,

00:41:34.391 --> 00:41:40.500
it will be unknown to 10^(-12
)meters.

00:41:40.500 --> 00:41:49.329
10^(-12)meters is what,
let's see?

00:41:49.329 --> 00:41:55.670
It's 1/100 of an atom size,
1/100 the size of an atom.

00:41:55.670 --> 00:41:59.849
So you see, these uncertainties
are not important in real life.

00:41:59.849 --> 00:42:02.463
So everything that you think
has a definite position and

00:42:02.463 --> 00:42:04.650
momentum actually has a slight
uncertainty,

00:42:04.650 --> 00:42:08.052
but the uncertainties don't
lead to any measurable

00:42:08.052 --> 00:42:12.289
consequences over any distances
that you can actually have.

00:42:12.289 --> 00:42:14.690
So what I'm trying to tell you
is, there are these waves.

00:42:14.690 --> 00:42:17.351
They do all kinds of things,
they do interference and

00:42:17.351 --> 00:42:19.963
everything, but the condition
for them is really the

00:42:19.963 --> 00:42:21.090
microscopic world.
 

00:42:21.090 --> 00:42:24.179
The minute the masses become
comparable to gram or kilogram

00:42:24.179 --> 00:42:26.150
and distances and slits and so
on,

00:42:26.150 --> 00:42:29.713
or like a meter or a
centimeter, these effects get

00:42:29.713 --> 00:42:30.659
washed out.
 

00:42:30.659 --> 00:42:34.940
But in the atomic scale,
they are seen.

00:42:34.940 --> 00:42:41.481
Now the final thing I want to
mention before moving on to a

00:42:41.481 --> 00:42:47.909
completely new topic is the role
of probability in quantum

00:42:47.909 --> 00:42:49.489
mechanics.
 

00:42:49.489 --> 00:42:53.230
We have seen that quantum
mechanics makes probabilistic

00:42:53.230 --> 00:42:54.199
predictions.
 

00:42:54.199 --> 00:42:56.730
It says if you do the double
slit experiment,

00:42:56.730 --> 00:43:00.121
I don't know where this guy
will land, but I'll give you the

00:43:00.121 --> 00:43:00.639
odds.
 

00:43:00.639 --> 00:43:04.449
Okay, now that looks like
something we have done many

00:43:04.449 --> 00:43:06.719
times in classical mechanics.
 

00:43:06.719 --> 00:43:08.989
For example,
if you have a coin and you

00:43:08.989 --> 00:43:11.320
throw the coin,
you flip it and you say,

00:43:11.320 --> 00:43:13.650
"Which way will it
land?"

00:43:13.650 --> 00:43:17.199
well, it's a very difficult
calculation to do,

00:43:17.199 --> 00:43:19.070
but it can be done in
principle, because a coin,

00:43:19.070 --> 00:43:23.429
once released from your hand,
can only land in one way.

00:43:23.429 --> 00:43:25.579
That's the determinism of
Newtonian mechanics.

00:43:25.579 --> 00:43:27.802
If you knew exactly how you
released it with what angle or

00:43:27.802 --> 00:43:29.967
momentum,
what's the viscosity of air,

00:43:29.967 --> 00:43:32.275
whatever you want,
if you give me all the numbers,

00:43:32.275 --> 00:43:33.480
I'll tell you it's head or
tails.

00:43:33.480 --> 00:43:35.219
There's no need to guess.
 

00:43:35.219 --> 00:43:38.090
In practice,
no one can do the calculation.

00:43:38.090 --> 00:43:40.481
What you do in practice is,
you throw the same coin 5,000

00:43:40.481 --> 00:43:43.260
times and you find out the odds
for head or tails and you say,

00:43:43.260 --> 00:43:45.409
"I predict that when you
throw it next time,

00:43:45.409 --> 00:43:50.389
it will be .51 chance that it
will be heads."

00:43:50.389 --> 00:43:52.599
That's how you give statistical
predictions.

00:43:52.599 --> 00:43:57.610
Now you did not have to use
statistics.

00:43:57.610 --> 00:44:00.601
You use it, because you cannot
really in practice do the hard

00:44:00.601 --> 00:44:01.300
calculation.
 

00:44:01.300 --> 00:44:03.739
In principle, you can.
 

00:44:03.739 --> 00:44:07.670
Secondly, if you toss a coin
and I hide it in my hand,

00:44:07.670 --> 00:44:10.050
I don't show it to you,
it's either head or tails,

00:44:10.050 --> 00:44:11.268
and I say, "What do you
think it is?"

00:44:11.268 --> 00:44:13.639
you'll say, "It's .1
chance that it's heads."

00:44:13.639 --> 00:44:16.090
And I look at it,
it may be head or it may be

00:44:16.090 --> 00:44:16.480
tail.
 

00:44:16.480 --> 00:44:18.349
Suppose I got head.
 

00:44:18.349 --> 00:44:22.400
It means that it was head even
before I opened my hand,

00:44:22.400 --> 00:44:23.000
right?
 

00:44:23.000 --> 00:44:25.179
The correct answer's already
inside my hand.

00:44:25.179 --> 00:44:26.150
I just didn't know it.
 

00:44:26.150 --> 00:44:28.059
I'm using odds,
but when I look at it,

00:44:28.059 --> 00:44:28.989
I get an answer.
 

00:44:28.989 --> 00:44:34.570
That's the answer it had even
before I looked.

00:44:34.570 --> 00:44:36.630
So I'll give another analogy
here.

00:44:36.630 --> 00:44:45.920
So this is a probability of
locating me somewhere.

00:44:45.920 --> 00:44:50.918
This is my home town,
Cheshire, this is Yale,

00:44:50.918 --> 00:44:55.010
and this is the infamous Route
10.

00:44:55.010 --> 00:44:57.396
So somebody has studied me for
a long time and said,

00:44:57.396 --> 00:45:00.110
"If you look for this guy,
here are the odds."

00:45:00.110 --> 00:45:04.503
Either he's working at home or
he's working at Yale,

00:45:04.503 --> 00:45:07.519
and sometimes he's driving,
okay?

00:45:07.519 --> 00:45:08.869
This is the probability.
 

00:45:08.869 --> 00:45:12.927
First thing to understand is
the spread out probability does

00:45:12.927 --> 00:45:15.679
not mean I am myself spread out,
okay?

00:45:15.679 --> 00:45:19.780
Unless I got into a terrible
accident on Route 10,

00:45:19.780 --> 00:45:21.789
I'm in only one place.
 

00:45:21.789 --> 00:45:24.217
So probability's being extended
doesn't mean the thing you're

00:45:24.217 --> 00:45:25.230
looking at is extended.
 

00:45:25.230 --> 00:45:27.840
I am in some sense a particle
which can be somewhere.

00:45:27.840 --> 00:45:29.539
These are the odds.
 

00:45:29.539 --> 00:45:34.429
Well, suppose you catch me here
on one of your many trials.

00:45:34.429 --> 00:45:36.811
If you catch me only once,
you don't know if the

00:45:36.811 --> 00:45:38.989
prediction's even good,
so you repeat it.

00:45:38.989 --> 00:45:41.367
You study me over many times
and you agree the person had got

00:45:41.367 --> 00:45:44.155
the right picture,
because after observing me

00:45:44.155 --> 00:45:48.668
many, many days you in fact get
the histogram that looks like

00:45:48.668 --> 00:45:49.268
this.
 

00:45:49.268 --> 00:45:52.635
The important thing is,
every time you catch me

00:45:52.635 --> 00:45:56.838
somewhere, I was already there;
you just happened to catch me

00:45:56.838 --> 00:45:57.269
there.
 

00:45:57.269 --> 00:46:00.179
I had a definite location.
 

00:46:00.179 --> 00:46:03.800
It was not known to you,
but I had it.

00:46:03.800 --> 00:46:07.496
I had a definite location
because in the macroscopic world

00:46:07.496 --> 00:46:10.416
I'm moving in,
my location is being constantly

00:46:10.416 --> 00:46:11.260
measured.
 

00:46:11.260 --> 00:46:14.556
You didn't ask or you didn't
find out, but I'm running

00:46:14.556 --> 00:46:16.050
through air molecules.
 

00:46:16.050 --> 00:46:16.900
I've slammed into them.
 

00:46:16.900 --> 00:46:18.510
They know that.
 

00:46:18.510 --> 00:46:20.518
I ran over this ant.
 

00:46:20.518 --> 00:46:22.780
That was the last thing the ant
knew, okay?

00:46:22.780 --> 00:46:26.704
So I'm leaving behind a trail
of destruction and they all keep

00:46:26.704 --> 00:46:28.119
track of where I am.
 

00:46:28.119 --> 00:46:29.730
My location is well known.
 

00:46:29.730 --> 00:46:32.110
You just happened to find out.
 

00:46:32.110 --> 00:46:37.170
But now let's change this
picture and say this is not me.

00:46:37.170 --> 00:46:40.719
This is an electron and it's
got two nuclei.

00:46:40.719 --> 00:46:43.630
This is nucleus 1 and this is
nucleus 2.

00:46:43.630 --> 00:46:46.768
It can be either near this
nucleus or that nucleus,

00:46:46.768 --> 00:46:49.404
and this is the
Y^(2) for the

00:46:49.404 --> 00:46:50.219
electron.
 

00:46:50.219 --> 00:46:53.617
That means it's the probability
you'll catch it here and you'll

00:46:53.617 --> 00:46:54.550
catch it there.
 

00:46:54.550 --> 00:46:58.496
Once again, if you catch the
electron, you will catch all of

00:46:58.496 --> 00:46:59.699
it in one place.
 

00:46:59.699 --> 00:47:02.273
It is wrong to think the
electronic charge is somehow

00:47:02.273 --> 00:47:03.710
spread out around the atom.
 

00:47:03.710 --> 00:47:04.579
It's not true.
 

00:47:04.579 --> 00:47:06.070
The charge is in one place.
 

00:47:06.070 --> 00:47:07.360
The odds are spread out.
 

00:47:07.360 --> 00:47:09.460
That looks just like my case.
 

00:47:09.460 --> 00:47:11.623
But the difference is,
if you catch the

00:47:11.623 --> 00:47:15.094
electron--let's in fact simplify
life and say there are only 2

00:47:15.094 --> 00:47:16.119
possibilities.
 

00:47:16.119 --> 00:47:19.550
Either it is near atom
1--nucleus 1 or nucleus 2,

00:47:19.550 --> 00:47:21.409
only 2 discrete choices.
 

00:47:21.409 --> 00:47:26.597
If you catch it near 2,
it is wrong to think that it

00:47:26.597 --> 00:47:29.650
was there before you got it.
 

00:47:29.650 --> 00:47:31.630
So where was it?
 

00:47:31.630 --> 00:47:34.940
It was not in any one place.
 

00:47:34.940 --> 00:47:39.719
It had no location till you
found its location.

00:47:39.719 --> 00:47:40.809
That's very strange.
 

00:47:40.809 --> 00:47:44.195
We think of measurement as
revealing a pre-existing

00:47:44.195 --> 00:47:45.889
property of the object.
 

00:47:45.889 --> 00:47:48.659
But in quantum theory,
it's not that you don't know

00:47:48.659 --> 00:47:49.989
where the electron is.
 

00:47:49.989 --> 00:47:50.840
It does not know.
 

00:47:50.840 --> 00:47:52.518
It is not anywhere.
 

00:47:52.518 --> 00:47:57.025
It's the act of measurement
that confers a location or

00:47:57.025 --> 00:47:59.320
position on the electron.
 

00:47:59.320 --> 00:48:02.764
That state of being,
where you can be either here or

00:48:02.764 --> 00:48:06.748
there, or simultaneously here or
there, has no analog in the

00:48:06.748 --> 00:48:08.099
classical world.
 

00:48:08.099 --> 00:48:11.514
If anybody tries to give you an
example, don't believe it,

00:48:11.514 --> 00:48:14.990
because there are no examples
in the macroscopic world that

00:48:14.990 --> 00:48:16.130
look like this.
 

00:48:16.130 --> 00:48:21.197
No analogies should satisfy
you, because this has no analog

00:48:21.197 --> 00:48:23.469
in the real world,
okay?

00:48:23.469 --> 00:48:26.179
So this is the interesting
thing in quantum mechanics.

00:48:26.179 --> 00:48:29.070
If this is a possible wave
function Y,

00:48:29.070 --> 00:48:32.175
electron near nucleus 1,
and that's a possible wave

00:48:32.175 --> 00:48:35.045
function Y,
electron near nucleus 2,

00:48:35.045 --> 00:48:37.070
you can add the two functions.
 

00:48:37.070 --> 00:48:39.829
That's another possible
function.

00:48:39.829 --> 00:48:41.809
But what does that describe?
 

00:48:41.809 --> 00:48:45.396
It describes an electron which
upon measurement could be found

00:48:45.396 --> 00:48:47.280
here and could be found there.
 

00:48:47.280 --> 00:48:50.380
It's not like finding me in
Cheshire or finding me in New

00:48:50.380 --> 00:48:52.070
Haven,
because in those cases,

00:48:52.070 --> 00:48:54.139
on a given day on a given
measurement,

00:48:54.139 --> 00:48:56.469
you can only get one answer,
depending on where I am.

00:48:56.469 --> 00:48:58.739
Right now if they look for me,
they can only find me here.

00:48:58.739 --> 00:49:01.039
They cannot find me anywhere
else.

00:49:01.039 --> 00:49:04.610
But in the case of the
electron, the one and the same

00:49:04.610 --> 00:49:07.768
electron, on a given trial,
at a given instant,

00:49:07.768 --> 00:49:10.789
is fully capable of being here
or there.

00:49:10.789 --> 00:49:15.750
It's like tossing a coin and
it's in my hand.

00:49:15.750 --> 00:49:18.907
We all know that when I reveal
it to you, you can only get one

00:49:18.907 --> 00:49:22.170
answer, now that the toss has
been done, it's got one answer.

00:49:22.170 --> 00:49:25.257
If it's a quantum mechanical
coin, you don't know,

00:49:25.257 --> 00:49:28.030
and it doesn't have a value
till you look.

00:49:28.030 --> 00:49:30.000
When you look,
it has a definite value.

00:49:30.000 --> 00:49:32.099
Before you look,
it doesn't have a definite

00:49:32.099 --> 00:49:32.500
value.
 

00:49:32.500 --> 00:49:34.514
That's exactly like saying,
when you looked,

00:49:34.514 --> 00:49:36.110
it goes through a definite
slit.

00:49:36.110 --> 00:49:39.800
When you don't look,
it's wrong to assume it went

00:49:39.800 --> 00:49:41.800
through a definite slit.
 

00:49:41.800 --> 00:49:42.880
Yes?
 

00:49:42.880 --> 00:49:45.918
Student:  Say you had a
double slit experiment but

00:49:45.918 --> 00:49:48.900
instead of having a screen that
went all the way in both

00:49:48.900 --> 00:49:52.070
directions,
you just sort of had _____

00:49:52.070 --> 00:49:52.780
screen.
 

00:49:52.780 --> 00:49:58.458
So then you would only be
looking at the final location of

00:49:58.458 --> 00:50:00.550
a _______ electron.
 

00:50:00.550 --> 00:50:02.860
The other half you would know.
 

00:50:02.860 --> 00:50:07.849
How would that work,
because location for some of

00:50:07.849 --> 00:50:10.969
them has to be ____________.
 

00:50:10.969 --> 00:50:13.034
Prof: The minute you
find the location to the

00:50:13.034 --> 00:50:15.059
accuracy of knowing which slit
it went through,

00:50:15.059 --> 00:50:17.599
you've got 2 slits or only 1 in
the experiment?

00:50:17.599 --> 00:50:21.088
Student:  You have 2
slits but only a half screen,

00:50:21.088 --> 00:50:23.018
and nothing on the other one.
 

00:50:23.018 --> 00:50:25.427
Prof: Oh,
you've got a screen that only

00:50:25.427 --> 00:50:26.820
comes to here,
you mean?

00:50:26.820 --> 00:50:27.440
Student:  Yes.
 

00:50:27.440 --> 00:50:30.143
Prof: Yes,
the real problem of location

00:50:30.143 --> 00:50:33.869
that I'm talking about here is
not when it hits the screen,

00:50:33.869 --> 00:50:36.099
but here, when you try to see
which hole it went through,

